<TITLE> Korea offers to install N-power plant </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 21 (bdnews24.com)South Korea has proposed to set up nuclear power plants in Bangladesh. The Korean offer came a week after the government signed a memorandum of understanding with Russia on generation of nuclear power. Earlier, China also made similar proposal. The head of a Korean delegation, deputy minister for foreign affairs and trade Lee Yong-Joon, proposed to install nuclear plants at the long overdue annual foreign secretary-level talks on Thursday in Dhaka. Foreign secretary Md Touhid Hossain led Bangladesh side at the talks that last took place in 1993. "They have offered to set up nuclear plants. We will go for the cheapest and the safest," state minister for foreign affairs Hasan Mahmud told reporters following his meeting with Yong-Joon. . "Korean is well-known for its supply of most advanced technology and safest nuclear power plant in the world. "We have discussed it at the meeting," he added. "If Bangladeshi government is interested in cooperating with us on nuclear power generation, we are ready to negotiate with the government," Yong-Joon told reporters after the meeting at foreign ministry. He said it was now up to the Bangladesh to decide about it. "They have offered us proposal to set up nuclear plants. "We will accept which will be cheapest and safest," Mahmud told reporters following his meeting with Yong-Joon. Yong-Joon said his country never experienced any nuclear accident in its 30 years in the field. He said Korean Electricity and Power Company (KEPCO), which 20 materialised nuclear plants, would negotiate with Bangladesh. Yong-Joon said he also discussed recruiting more Bangladeshi workers once the ongoing global economic downturn was over.
